Yes, there are several Maven SDKs/APIs for programmatic access:

## Maven Invoker API
For running Maven commands programmatically:

```java
Invoker invoker = new DefaultInvoker();
InvocationRequest request = new DefaultInvocationRequest();
request.setPomFile(new File("pom.xml"));
request.setGoals(Arrays.asList("help:describe"));
request.setProperties(properties);
InvocationResult result = invoker.execute(request);
```

## Maven Model API
For parsing POM files and accessing project structure:

```java
MavenXpp3Reader reader = new MavenXpp3Reader();
Model model = reader.read(new FileReader("pom.xml"));
Build build = model.getBuild();
List<Plugin> plugins = build.getPlugins();
```

## Maven Embedder
For embedding Maven runtime:

```java
MavenEmbedder embedder = new MavenEmbedder();
MavenExecutionRequest request = new DefaultMavenExecutionRequest();
MavenExecutionResult result = embedder.execute(request);
```

## Third-party tools
- **Maven Wrapper scripts** - Shell/batch scripts for consistent Maven versions
- **Takari Maven Plugin** - Enhanced Maven tooling
- **Maven Daemon** - Faster Maven execution via daemon process

For your specific use case (getting lifecycle phase information), the **Maven Model API** would be most appropriate since it can directly access POM configuration and plugin bindings without executing Maven commands.

