Based on the search results, I can provide you with comprehensive information about Nx project configuration JSON schema format for targets and scripts:

## Nx Project Configuration JSON Schema Format

The full machine readable schema is available on GitHub for both project.json and nx.json configuration files.

### Project Structure and Schema Reference

The project.json file includes a `$schema` property that references the Nx project schema: `"$schema": "../../node_modules/nx/schemas/project-schema.json"`

### Targets Configuration

Each project has targets configured to run an executor with a specific set of options. In this snippet, cart has two targets defined - build and test.

The basic structure for targets includes:

Each executor definition has an executor property and, optionally, an options and a configurations property. executor is a string of the form [package name]:[executor name].

Example project.json with targets:
```json
{
  "name": "myproject",
  "$schema": "../../node_modules/nx/schemas/project-schema.json",
  "sourceRoot": "apps/myproject/src",
  "projectType": "application",
  "targets": {
    "build": {
      "executor": "@nx/webpack:webpack",
      "options": {
        "outputPath": "dist/apps/myproject"
      }
    },
    "test": {
      "executor": "@nx/jest:jest",
      "options": {}
    }
  }
}
```

### Scripts Integration

Nx merges package.json scripts with any targets defined in project.json. If you only wish for some scripts to be used as Nx targets, you can specify them in the includedScripts property of the project's package.json.(no content)You can invoke nx build mylib or nx test mylib without any extra configuration when scripts are defined in package.json.

Example with scripts integration:
```json
{
  "name": "mylib",
  "scripts": {
    "test": "jest",
    "build": "tsc -p tsconfig.lib.json"
  },
  "nx": {
    "targets": {
      "build": {
        "inputs": ["production", "^production"],
        "outputs": ["{workspaceRoot}/dist/libs/mylib"],
        "dependsOn": ["^build"]
      }
    },
    "includedScripts": ["test", "build"]
  }
}
```

### Target Defaults in nx.json

Target defaults provide ways to set common options for a particular target in your workspace. When building your project's configuration, we merge it with up to 1 default from this map.(no content)Instead of defining the same configuration across all of our projects, we can leverage target defaults so that we don't need to maintain the same configuration everywhere.

Example nx.json with target defaults:
```json
{
  "$schema": "./node_modules/nx/schemas/nx-schema.json",
  "targetDefaults": {
    "build": {
      "inputs": ["production", "^production"],
      "dependsOn": ["^build"]
    },
    "serve": {
      "options": {
        "port": 5000
      }
    }
  }
}
```

### Configuration Properties

The configurations property provides extra sets of values that will be merged into the options map.

### Command-based Targets

Nx also supports simple command-based targets without executors:
```json
{
  "targets": {
    "echo": {
      "command": "echo 'hello world'"
    }
  }
}
```

### Key Properties in project.json

The main properties include:
- `name`: Project name
- `$schema`: Reference to the JSON schema
- `sourceRoot`: Source directory path
- `projectType`: "application" or "library"
- `targets`: Object containing target configurations
- `tags`: Array of project tags

The only functional difference is that tasks that use executors must be defined in a project.json. Nx merges the two files to get each project's configuration.

